awd_titl_txt: Improving Technician Training in Automation Technologies for Advanced Manufacturing
awd_abstract_narration:
Recent advances in automation technologies are creating new employment opportunities for technicians in advanced manufacturing. To maintain a competitive advantage, many manufacturers are implementing these new technologies to create Industry 4.0 smart factories. Programmable Logic Controllers (PLCs) play a central role in this new automation architecture and require extensive training to implement and maintain. To meet industry needs in Northeastern Florida, Florida State College at Jacksonville will develop a new curriculum that focuses on PLCs and related automation technologies. To do so, the project will create a new track in an existing engineering technology program that will enable students to earn three national certifications in automation. Given regional demographics, this project also provides an opportunity to broaden participation of women and minorities in the advanced manufacturing workforce. For example, to increase participation in academic pathways leading to technical careers in advanced manufacturing, the project will develop a dual enrollment program in mechatronics at a local high school. In addition, it will offer hands-on learning experiences using advanced manufacturing technologies for high school students and provide professional development for high school teachers. 

The goal of this project is to increase the number of skilled technicians who can implement and maintain PLCs, robotics, and mechatronics systems. To achieve this goal, the project will:  1) implement a new, four-course PLC program track to enable students to earn national PLC industry credentials; 2) establish a new automation education lab for students including Augmented/Virtual Reality (AR/VR) learning software and PLC/automation hardware and software; 3) offer hands-on learning experiences using AR/VR software, robot literacy activities, and advanced manufacturing technologies for high school students; and 4) provide professional development for secondary and postsecondary instructors. The impact of the project on student demographics will be assessed by analyzing institutional data at the beginning and end of the project. Findings will be disseminated through national and regional venues such as the Florida Advanced Technological Education Center, the First Coast Manufacturing Association, the Florida College System, and the Northeast Florida STEM HUB. This project is funded by the Advanced Technological Education program that focuses on the education of technicians for the advanced-technology fields that drive the nation’s economy.

This award reflects NSF's statutory mission and has been deemed worthy of support through evaluation using the Foundation's intellectual merit and broader impacts review criteria.

Recruit and enroll 100 students in the newPLC track and courses by the end of the project period providing students with an opportunityto earn multiple national industry certifications and Objective 1.4: Increase enrollment ofunderrepresented populations by 5 percent, specifically focusing on women and minorities, tocreate a diverse technician workforce. The total enrollment in PLC courses over the course of theproject is 76 students. A total of 48 students were enrolled in courses in 2024, and 28 studentsare currently enrolled as of Spring 2025. Based on data shared, the project team has enrolled76% of the expected students to new PLC courses, showing a substantial increase from 2023(see Figure 1).

Goal 3: Offer hands-on, experiential immersion experiences using AR/VR software, robotliteracy activities, and 3D modeling programs introducing addictive and subtractivemanufacturing to underrepresented populations and professional development forpostsecondary and K-12 faculty/staff.The first objective within Goal 3 is to promote career pathway awareness and to strengthenmath and science skills for 60 precollege school students (30 in Years 2 and 3) fromunderrepresented populations over the project period will participate in learning activities.Table 12 highlights the engagement and achievements of precollege students involved in variouslearning initiatives. This table presents a comprehensive overview of the project team’s activities,such as hosting the MFK Warriors FIRST LEGO League robotics team and holding advisoryroles for Twin Lake Academy Middle School Robowolves. The table highlights the number ofparticipants, their grade levels, and any awards received, illustrating Next Gen PLC Tech’s broadimpact on students ranging from the 4th to 7th grade. The achievements listed, including awardsat regional and state tournaments, underscore the significant accomplishments of these younglearners. The project’s success in outreach with middle and high school students showcases theproject’s commitment to enhancing STEM education and strengthening precollege students’mathematics and science skills. In addition to success with precollege students, the projectteam also noted increased engagement with parents of MFK Warriors, highlighting the range ofsupport students are receiving through these learning activities.
